title: Z-Axis Replacement for CTC, Flashforge, Replicator with integrated spacer

description.text:
This file includes the z-axis replacement parts with a spacer for propper installation of the z-axis linear slides.  
This thing reduce the number of necessary screws (especially under the board) and make the adjustment of the z-axis much easier.  
hope you will get rid of your problems with the z-axis and wobbling.

Installation:
  • Just print the 3 parts in 100% scale, remove the top and the bottom original parts for the z-axis linear slides and motor mount.
  • Insert the bottom part of the z-axis replacement first and guide the linear slides inside the holes propperly.
  • place the spacer above the bottom part and install the 4 screws for the stepper motor (not tight / slack)
  • install the top part now (not tight either)
  • Take a ruler and measure the correct placement for the two parts (center between the 2 sides of the frame)
  • Start your printer and use the Jog Mode to drive the z-axis bed to the bottom (your stepper motor will center intself. move the printer bed up-again
  • thighten all screws

I used Blender to smooth the original STL which was a little noisy and then used OpenSCAD to hollow it out, make a flat bottom (which got messed up by the smoothing) and add the triangle nubs for making the croaking noise. If you have not seen one of these, you take a dowel or stick or something and slide it across the nubs and it simulates a toad croaking. Seems to work pretty well (perhaps I can upload a video later)--though the sound was not as deep as I had hoped with version 1.0. I designed a version 2.0 that has a slightly smaller and narrower opening with a slight expansion that I thought might amplify the sound a little. Haven't had a chance to print it yet, so please share if you make it.
I have also included a picture of the painted version--this was for a pond themed project for my son's preschool. Have fun!

I printed this in white PET+ at 25% fill--I tried at lower fill, but PET doesn't bridge quite as well and so it had some trouble filling across some of the upper sections.  The full size is quite large--I think I printed it at 75%.  I have also been curious to see if the amount of infill changes the tone at all...

description.text: This part is a small piece to mount the PBC Linear SIMO stages from the Aluminatus to a 2060 profile.

The part contains 5 holes - 3 are countersunk and are spaced 20mm apart to be connected to 2060 profiles.  Use M5x10mm bolts here.  Three are probably unnecessary, but the holes are there.  
The outer two holes are intended to be tapped for M6 bolts.  These line up with the SIMO holes where you can use an M6x20 or M6x25 bolt for mounting.  
Print out two copies (one for each end of the SIMO stage.  You will need 4-6 M5 bolts and 4 M6 bolts.  
This part is also being laser cut in 5mm aluminum, however the cutter won't be done for another week and I want to try out my SIMO stages today, so this is the short-term solution. 1079 (3mm shaft with #2-56 screws)
1081 (4mm shaft with #4-40 screws)

2675 (1/4" shaft scooter mount with M3 screws) It has two holes with strain relief to attach a string or wire. Just tie a nut or similar to the string, or tie a knot in it to stop it pulling through. If you have any requests for more features, just comment below.

There are only two dimensions to select:
1) The radius of the spool from the center to the flat section (not including top and bottom flanges).
2) Width of spool from top flange to bottom, not including flanges. Both dimensions are in mm. The flanges are always 5mm wide/high, with a 2mm rim top and bottom. Recommend 'High' Polygon count unless your spool is huge. You will need six screws with ~15mm long threads to attach it. Three will do for low torque applications. The hub can be mounted either way, but you'll need to mount the hub before the spool otherwise you won't be able to access the machine screws. It should be printed without support. title: Aluminum turbine rotor cast in ABS mold

description.text: An aluminum casting of a turbine, using an ABS mold. My understanding is the original turbine pattern is here. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:590416, user by Engi-IRL. I modified a possible remix, from another user, prk_mek. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:680664

A turbine file was considerably scaled down to about 1.25 inches in diameter.
The ABS molds were printed with 0.20mm layers at medium speed. 120 minutes... 22 grams ABS if my notes are correct... The (Afinia default) support angle was reduced from 30 to just 10 degrees to minimize support at the curve of the blades' tips.
The fins are so thin (about 0.02 inches) that there would be no way to remove support from such skinny and curved crevasses.
And it looks like most of the fins came out in the casting. Aluminum was poured at 1250F. It was a small amount for a small part, so there wasn't much smoke. The hot rotor did melt through the mold face, but it just didn't have sufficient BTUs to scorch the plastic... Cooled rather quickly.
The semi-finished casting weighs about 7.5 grams. I made several modifications to this prototype centrifugal casting machine I've been working on, and I searched for something to test it on. This turbine was good looking and appeared challenging. I'd estimate the casting came out 90% good, and 10% defects.
A better gating system (sprue, runners, gates, vents, etc.) should fix most of the 10%.
ABS molds are new territory so there's much trial and error.
This project follows a few prior explorations into what casting metal in a 3D printed mold may have to offer. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:735587 aluminum heat sink
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:733205 gravity cast tube

And requires a spring (a printed option is in sources). The flag also requires a fork to cradle the Z-smooth rod to stop it from rotating.

description.text: A remix of Nylocke's EZFlex extruder, which is a direct replacement for Seemecnc's Ezstruder, but modified to work with a planetary geared motor. The bowden tube runs all the way to the hobbed gear, allowing this to be used with flexible filaments. Nylocke's original design: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/ezflexstruder NOTEs: In the picture, the screw at the top left has an absurd amount of nuts on it only because it was too long and I couldn't find a shorter one while putting this together. Also, the passthrough connectors have a little play in them, so a twist tie wrapped around the locking collet to keep it from jiggling is handy.

Rough Bill of Materials: Planetary Geared Nema 17 motor, recommended gear ratio of 5:1 M7 hobbed gear for 8mm shaft, I recommend the one from TriDPrinting, it's excellent Printed Adapter Printed Arm Printed Body (called plate in the current file name) 1x M8x20ish bolt 2x M8 washer 1x Passthrough bowden connector, from E3D or DTA-Labs 1x 608 bearing 1x ezstruder spring (need to figure out the exact specs) 4x M3x12 screws (I think that's the correct length, will check)
A handful of long (30mm or longer I think) M3 screws (I'll figure this out too) A handful of M3 nuts 1x small ziptie ASSEMBLY:
1) Print all three pieces. The arm will need some support material. 2) Screw the adapter onto the motor using the M3x12 screws. There's a gap one side of the adapter, that's the side the bearing will be on later. 3) Assemble the bearing arm:
a) push the 608 bearing into the retaining slot on the arm
b) push an M8 washer in above and below the bearing
c) with the bearing and washers lined up, push the M8 bolt down through them...the plastic should keep the bolt in place, but if your printer made the holes loose, use an M8 nut on the end 4) Screw the main body of the extruder down onto the adapter. The gap in the adapter has to be on the left as you drop the body down over it. 5) Screw on the bearing arm, and wedge in the spring. The ziptie goes around the spring side of the arm, pulling it flush against the body of the extruder, since the spring will try to angle it out a little. This might not be 100% necessary, but it will guarantee that the bearing presses flat against the filament. 6) Screw in the pass through bowden connector. 7) Install the bowden tube. To make sure it's easy to start filament through it, use a knife and give the inner edge of the top of the tube a slight angle. The current design is a little tight, so you'll have to fight with the tube to get it all the way up through, but it'll hold well. 8) Install the hobbed gear on the motor shaft, and be sure to line up it up with the bowden tube. Done! Mount it to any EZStruder compatible mount, and feed filament down through the bearing arm. Congratulations, you now have a bullet proof, easy to load and unload extruder with ****tons of torque, go you!

title: Kossel mini e3d v6 clip with mounting holes for 40x40x20 blowers and shroud.

description.text: This is a work in progress. The mount has a pair of holes each side for blower mounting, I just used some 40x20 blowers from ebay/amazon (e.g. http://www.amazon.co.uk/40x20mm-Plastic-Housing-Computer-Cooling/dp/B00N41AC1Y). You should continue to use the cooling fan supplied with the e3d hot end as the blowers will not cool the e3d heatsink. I'm currently using the mount + 2 of the small blower attachments. I've found that the big shroud isn't really needed and gets in the way of removing nozzles/can occasionally clip the bulldog clips holding my print surface to the heated bed. The scad file for the mount plus shrouds is currently a mess, I'll share it if/when I tidy it up a bit.

The mount is dead easy, shouldn't require anything special.  
The blower nozzles should print fairly easily on their sides, I'd recommend using XT/PET/ABS or something slightly more heat resistant than PLA, although if you're always running the fans PLA might be fine. I just used some aluminium tape to hold them to the blowers, they're really light so don't need anything more.  
The shroud (if you're going to use it) should probably be printed in something other than PLA as it is very close to the heater block. I sliced and printed it with cura with line type support "touching everywhere". The support should be fairly easy to remove as the shroud has quite an open structure.

description.text:
As many guys I started with a Mendel90. My printer was bulit according nophead github files with some changes due to parts availability. If you print PLA all is fine but when starting with ABS or other stuff a very small smell of a wind can destroy your print. I looked on thingiverse and in several online resources but nothing was appropriate to cover the Dibond version. Ok, my printer frame is from 3mm aluminium sheets but there is no difference in general. As I am not using any 300mm spool the customised holder is a bit smaller and we can use one of the holes of the origin holder for the covers. If you want to use the big ones please consider the spool holder to be app. 50mm higher. The enclosed holder is designed for a 12mm rod. Nonetheless I use it for an 8mm rod with a bearing spool holder. The filament guide rod was a 3/8" carbon tube from kiting. Please use whatever you find ;). The guide has been mounted backwards to ensure that the PTFE tubing is always running as a nice bow to the extruder.
The cover plates are made from corrugated cardbox material. Of course, you can use Dibond, Acrylic or something similar with 3mm thickness but cardbox is the cheapest. The only parts which I designed are covers and the small end caps itself. The remaining parts are taken from the things mentioned under remix. A suitable front housing with doors you can find here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:755654 Update 2017-03-22: As I was out for a longer time here now the last update. Some pictures will follow within next month.
Changes for V1.2: End cap now scaled correctly. As I have had issues with entangled filament I changed holding of the spools to a bearing supported version. Since then no problems anymore. The part spool holder was customised and will fit to many spools (may be all between 500g and 1kg). Update 2015-04-06: Just did some small corrections on the cover plates due to copy-paste issues. -> V1.1

You need for the cover:
5 fixing block.stl
1 rear fixing block.stl
17 pcs. cap screw M4x16
1 pc. cap screw M4x20 for the rear fixing block
17 pcs. washer M4 x 9mm x 0.8mm
1 set cover plates see PDF or DWG
2 holes 4.5mm on left rear frame as per attached drawing. You need for the filament guide:
1 filamentfuehrung.stl
1 rod app. dia. 8-9mm L=308mm
2 pcs. cap screw M3x10
2 pcs. washer M3 x 7mm x 0.5mm
2 holes 3.5mm into the frames to be drilled as per your need You need for the filament holder:
2 filament_holder_20150322-final.stl
4 pcs. cap screw M4x16
8 pcs. washer M4 x 9mm x 0.8mm
4 pcs. nyloc nut M4
1 rod app. dia. 12 L=336mm
4 holes 4.5mm into the frames to be drilled as per your need V1.2: You need for the spool holder:
2 spool_holde_dia60_dia40_h17.stl
3 clip.stl
2 bearings 608 (from old spool holder;)
1 (threaded) rod 8mm L=336mm instead of the 12mm from the filament holder You need for the fan guard:
1 fan guard.stl
4 pcs. nut M4 to fix the origin screws (longer screws might be required in case the fan is mounted)
2 pcs. wing nut M4 to fix the 2nd fan guard
1 small piece of active carbon filter material from a cooker hood
Just use the printed guard as sketch for the filter and do the holes with a soldering iron. All parts to be printed with 50% infill . Depending on the size of the washers used for levelling the print bed it might be necessary to change the end position of the firmware (mostly in configuration.h) from #define Y_MAX_POS 100 to #define Y_MAX_POS 98 to avoid contact between bed and back cover.

The second hand was printed then the tiny shaft was heated with a lighter and pressed onto the clock second shaft. It stayed on for awhile before it popped off so I then used the smallest dab of superglue to secure it to the second shaft and it's been on there ever since. Be careful if you try this though, to much glue will bind up the whole clock it you get it in the tube for the second hand shaft.

description.text:
These are cases for the new AZSMZ Mini controller board and LCD display board. This new 32 bit controller board runs Smoothieware and was my choice for a low-cost, high-performance controller for the Kossel 2020 delta printer I built. I've designed the case to allow a 40mm fan to be mounted to provide direct cooling for the stepper motor drivers.  
The holes in the cases were sized with the intention of tapping them with an M3 thread (this includes the  controller board mounting holes). Lids have holes to insert M3 capscrews.  
The mounting holes on the main board case were spaced to allow mounting to a standard Kossel 2020 frame design.  
UPDATE: V8 is major update from previous versions. Lots of little things were tweaked. The outlet air vent was changed, and slots along the top were changed and widened to allow stepper motor and limit switch connectors to fit through (without the need to remove the connectors to thread the wires through).
Modelling was done in DesignSpark Mechanical. RSDOC file included
Support may be needed in a few places - depends on your printer.

I had to remove the board from the case to replace a burnt-up power connector, and I was tired of having to remove the connectors from the motor wires, endstops, etc in order to thread the wires through. This board now has almost 1300 hours of printing time on it.

comments.text: There is an interesting twist in the open source licensing issue you mention. Although the AZSMZ is a clearly original design and isn't violating any other licenses, the designer has another board which he calls a "SmartRamps" that may indeed violate the Ramps 1.4 open source license. It is basically a direct copy of the Ramps 1.4 board with an EEPROM added so that it will work with an Arduino Due board. The fact that he chose to make the AZSMZ open-source, and then not follow through completely is a somewhat different issue. description.text: This pipette is based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64977 but with a few modifications. You can see the pipette in action here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nqb27um8KTk One important modification was to remove the threaded bolt from the plunger, and redesign the plunger so that a long (75mm) M4 bolt could be inserted through the length of the plunger replacing the original thread (see the detailed picture of the plunger). The thumb gears have also been modified to accept the M4 rod. The top part was made a lot bulkier so it could more easily be printed. Also, all models were rotated around the X axis and set for printing. Although all parts fit nicely together, I have been struggling a bit to get it to work. The bottom part was not fully airtight (and it really has to) but that could easily be solved by painting the membrane chamber with a good few coats of ABS juice. Also fitting the straw with a bit of ABS juice where the straw enters seals off any possibility of air escaping along the straw. The membrane (I used lab gloves) also easily splits and replacing the membrane is a bit of work. In my last reinstall I added an extra membrane which seems to work very well, even with actual 200 microliter tips! (which fit snuggly on top of straws, who would've guessed ...) I'll be testing its consistency (will it be below 10 microliter???) in a real lab later this week.

Print all parts (thumb wheel twice). I printed on a printrbot/Wallace++ clone with a layer thickness of 0.3mm. Screw a M4 75mm long bolt all the way through the plunger Continue with directions of the original design at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64977

Turret themed chess set for a board with ~1in squares. 
I'm working on making a chess board and due to certain constraints, I needed smaller than usual chess pieces (~1" base). Seeing how I was already going to be making them I figured I'd create my own design instead of just scaling someone else's. I purposely stayed away from too many details on the pieces because my printer and I are in a disagreement regarding calibration and I don't want to spend my all my free time cleaning up prints. I would love to see someone detail these out (wink wink nudge nudge).

The full set should fit on a cupcake but check for crashes just in case. All of the overhangs are equal to or less than 45 degs so supports aren't required. If you're going to print the pieces individually be warned that they are a little spindly and you may need to tweak your settings.
